  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Letter to Kim, Minister of the Board
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit this letter. Observing the words of the ancients, I glimpse your character and conduct. When a worthy man extends the Way, a sage minister makes it his first duty to become like Yao and Shun. When the world seeks talent, eminent scholars feel shame at merely following the hermits Chao Fu and Hsu Yu. In ancient times, such truths were merely recorded in books; now we look to them together in the halls of virtue.

    I respectfully behold you, noble Minister—your clarity fills the middle way, your depth moves through the world. With your lofty name you bring order to all things; with your complete virtue you steady the age. Like a peak touching a cloudless sky, like autumn moonlight gleaming in still waters. Once your orchids graced the palace courts, your bamboo rode the vermillion carriage. You departed to share the Son of Heaven's burdens, you returned to comfort the hopes of distant lands. How much more so in that province—its gates opening to the waters of Yüeh, its windows framing the peaks of Wu! There the winds of Yuan Hong's fan blow, taming the waters' turbulent rage; there the paths of Hsieh Yün flow, bringing spring to the fishing grounds.

    When the morning drums beat their song and a hundred virtues spread their renown, you ascended to receive the imperial grace, your light rising to celestial heights. Holding your noble name as precious treasure, who would dare question the realm's confusion? Holding your righteous office as sacred trust, you fashion schemes to strengthen the nation. Yet you receive such honors humbly, your rectitude unmarred by pride. You gather talent from mountain hollows and forest streams; you find joy in wine, poetry, and music.

    Long have you heard the Emperor's open heart; patiently have you witnessed the Four Quarters' disappointment. Now the owl's cry fades, the phoenix's time returns. Like the great talents of old, you await the compass of guidance. Like those of steadfast will, you soon shall show your devotion to the capital. Ascending the jade steps, sitting to govern the realm—this exceeds even the dreams within the moon, for it shall bring spring eternal to all beneath heaven.

    Thus you shall achieve the great designs of Yao and Shun, forever strengthening the state, and embrace the modest integrity of Chao Fu and Hsu Yu without withdrawing your service. I, having traveled far with humble wares, ashamed they bring not great price, merely beg to approach your tent as a student of your wisdom. My heart overflows with longing, prayer, and reverent trembling.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yao and Shun: legendary sage-emperors of ancient China, representing the ideals of virtuous rule'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Chao Fu and Hsu Yu: legendary hermits who refused office to preserve their integrity'
  - key: ''
    value: The references to Yuan Hong, Hsieh Yün, and others are classical allusions to wise ministers and their virtues
  - key: ''
    value: This letter employs the formal epistolary style of Tang-era Korean scholars, blending Confucian ideals with elegant classical rhetoric
